Emerging Role of Oligodendrocytes Malfunction in the Progression of Alzheimer's Disease
Introduction
AD has a complex and insufficiently understood etiology involving a dynamic interplay between genetic predisposition, environmental influences, epigenetic modifications, and dysregulated molecular pathways (Talwar et al.
2016
). Generally, AD is categorized into genetic (familial) and sporadic forms, with the latter being the predominant type observed in clinical populations. Genetic AD is a rarely occurring subtype resulting from mutations in APP, PSEN1, or PSEN2, which drive early-onset AD (EOAD) neurodegeneration typically manifesting before the age of 65 (Maurer et al.
1997
). In contrast, sporadic AD, which comprises over 95% of cases, lacks a clear inheritance pattern and is primarily influenced by the
APOE4
allele along with various environmental and epigenetic factor. EOAD, often associated with genetic mutations, exhibits a more aggressive disease course driven by increased Aβ production, whereas late-onset AD (LOAD), is largely multifactorial, characterized by impaired Aβ clearance, neuroinflammation, and oxidative stress (Strobel
n.d.
). Despite advances in understanding pathology onset, and progression, the multifactorial nature of Alzheimer's disease has hindered the development of a unified theory. Several hypotheses, including the cholinergic, amyloid cascade, neuroinflammatory, and oxidative stress have been proposed, each shedding light on distinct aspects of the disease's complexity (Liu et al.
2019
).

Emerging Role of Oligodendrocytes Malfunction in the Progression of Alzheimer's Disease
Introduction
Similar to microglia, astrocytes become reactive in response to Alzheimer's disease pathology, a process known as astrogliosis. Reactive astrocytes undergo morphological changes, including hypertrophy and upregulation of glial fibrillary acidic protein (GFAP) (Kato et al.
1998
). While these astrocytes can form a protective glial scar around Aβ plaques to limit neurotoxicity, they may also contribute to neuroinflammation by releasing proinflammatory cytokines and ROS (Monterey et al.
2021
). The interaction between microglia, astrocytes, and neurons is essential for maintaining CNS homeostasis. However, in AD, dysfunctional crosstalk with microglia leads to sustained neuroinflammation and oxidative stress (Hansen et al.
2018
). Conversely, astrocytes can also interface with neurons to promote synaptic repair, regulate synaptic transmission, and preserve the structural and functional integrity of the blood-brain barrier (BBB) (Zhang et al.
2024b
).

Emerging Role of Oligodendrocytes Malfunction in the Progression of Alzheimer's Disease
Oligodendrocyte Progenitor Cells (OPC) in Alzheimer's Disease
The animal models of AD have provided evidence of oligodendrocyte progenitor cell decline in density, and the following myelin integrity impairment in the hippocampus associated with age (Table
1
). Progressive changes in 3xTg AD mice were primarily observed in 6-month-old animals as morphological atrophy, which intensified over time, leading to OPC hypertrophy surrounded by Aβ plaques (Vanzulli et al.
2020
). Comparable disturbances in OPC have been documented in the APP/PS1 mouse model, with the earliest decline in progenitor cells number detected in 9-month-old animals. As the pathology advances, 14-month-old mice OPC exhibit pronounced morphological alterations, including cellular shrinkage, increased branching, and signs of dystrophy (Chacon-De-La-Rocha et al.
2020
). These findings demonstrate that while OPC degeneration and morphological disruption are characteristic markers of aging, AD appears to significantly accelerate the onset and progression of these pathological processes.
OPC have emerged as pivotal players in the clearance of Aβ, with their dysfunction has been linked to disruptions caused by Aβ accumulation. NG2 glial cells have been identified as novel contributors to Aβ clearance through mechanisms such as autophagy and endocytosis. While the role of OPC in Aβ clearance is often considered less significant compared to microglial activity, research underscores that impairments in autophagic processes within these progenitor cells substantially contribute to the progression of AD (Li et al.
2013
).

Emerging Role of Oligodendrocytes Malfunction in the Progression of Alzheimer's Disease
Oligodendrocyte Progenitor Cells (OPC) in Alzheimer's Disease
At the same time, a correlation between OPC presence and Aβ levels in cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) from AD patients has been proposed as a critical factor in disease pathogenesis, highlighting the nuanced and multifaceted role of OPC in neurodegenerative processes (Nielsen et al.
2013
). The clearance of Aβ and cellular debris by oligodendrocyte precursor cells leads to an upregulation of clusterin production (Beiter et al.
2024
), which could contribute to the worsening of AD pathology due to its role in mediating regulation of Aβ-induced neurotoxicity (Foster et al.
2019
). OPC from adult brain have also been identified as a cell type secreting Aβ
1-42
, which is likely released in vivo in association with defective oligodendrocyte differentiation. According to recent data, this pathology may play a crucial role in the initiation and progression of sporadic AD (Nihonmatsu-Kikuchi et al.
2021
). The restoration of the myelinating oligodendrocyte pool is also linked to morphological changes in OPC that occur in the presence of Aβ plaques. In this context, OPC transition into senescent, proinflammatory cells that are unable to differentiate into mature oligodendrocytes. This conversion is regarded as a pivotal determinant of AD progression, as the ablation of senescent OPC in the APP/PS1 mouse model has been shown to significantly improve memory impairment (Zhang et al.
2019
).

Emerging Role of Oligodendrocytes Malfunction in the Progression of Alzheimer's Disease
Myelin Impairment in Alzheimer's Disease
Desai
et al
.
have conducted extensive research using 3xTg AD mice, showing various pathologies in the myelin sheath and oligodendrocytes (Table
1
). Abnormalities in 2-month-old 3xTg AD mice's myelin sheath mostly manifested as disruptions in integrity, such as splitting of the major dense line and the accumulation of dense bodies in the Schaffer collateral pathway of the hippocampus (Desai et al.
2009
). Importantly, the reduction in the CA1 hippocampus region and entorhinal cortex, as well as the decline in the function of oligodendrocytes, which were more prone to apoptosis, occurred prior to Aβ plaques, even though OL degeneration was driven by soluble Aβ oligomers (Desai et al.
2010
,
2011
). By 2 months of age, APP/PS1 mice exhibited a thicker myelin sheath and a shorter internodal distance compared to wild-type mice (Wu et al.
2017b
). By 12 months, they also displayed a regionally restricted decline in oligodendrocyte density, specifically in the CA3 and CA4 regions of the hippocampus (DeFlitch et al.
2022
). Myelin abnormalities were evident even at earlier stages in 5xTg AD mice. At 1 month of age, transgenic mice exhibited a thinner myelin sheath, accompanied by splitting of the myelin layers and occasional ballooning, where the sheath became swollen (Gu et al.
2018
). Moreover, an increase in abnormally myelinated axons was observed (Wu et al.
2017b
). During the course of aging, myelin breakdown and OPC decline became apparent, with progressive deterioration in the hippocampus, particularly the dentate gyrus. By 12 months of age, this deterioration expanded to encompass all regions of the hippocampus (Zota et al.
2024
).

Emerging Role of Oligodendrocytes Malfunction in the Progression of Alzheimer's Disease
Myelin Impairment in Alzheimer's Disease
Since preventing myelin loss remains unfeasible at present, improving the process of myelination is proposed as a potentially more advantageous strategy to improve cognitive outcomes (Wang et al.
2018
). Genetically and pharmacologically enhancing myelin renewal could potentially improve performance in memory-related tasks. For instance, conditional deletion of the muscarinic M1 receptor (M1R) in OPC changed the density of newly formed myelin sheaths and enlarged the potential for repair. Improved myelin repair in these mice displayed significant improvement in the Morris water maze and novel object recognition (NOR) tasks (Chen et al.
2021
). However, myelin renewal within the surroundings of Aβ deposits seems to decline compared to areas lacking deposits, possibly due to inhibitory cues from senescent OPC induced by Aβ deposits (Zhang et al.
2019
).
This unforeseen issue alters the perspective on future research, suggesting the necessity to investigate not only myelin sheath changes in Alzheimer's disease but also the underlying correlation between the hallmarks of AD, oligodendrocyte precursor cells, and mature oligodendrocytes.

Emerging Role of Oligodendrocytes Malfunction in the Progression of Alzheimer's Disease
Role of Oligodendrocytes in Neuroinflammation
Disease-Associated Oligodendrocytes (DAO) in AD
Due to limited research in the present field, the translational potential of DAO as a therapeutic target requires further investigation. SERPINA3N has been identified in the brains of
post-mortem
AD patients, and DAO has been observed in regions surrounding Aβ plaques, suggesting potential avenues for therapeutic intervention aimed at mitigating DAO-mediated damage in AD (Kenigsbuch et al.
2022
). However, transcriptional responses involving DAO in AD differ significantly between mice and humans (Pandey et al.
2022
). Additionally, the transcriptomic signature of DAO overlaps with that of disease-associated astrocytes (DAA) and microglia (DAM), including the upregulation of a similar set of genes (e.g.,
C4b, Serpina3n, B2m
) in response to amyloid and tau pathology. Despite these shared molecular features, glial cell types exhibit distinct functional profiles. For instance, astrocytes predominantly display interferon-related responses, whereas oligodendrocytes show changes associated with demyelination and apoptosis (Lee et al.
2021
). Moreover, while DAM activation is heavily dependent on TREM2, DAO activation appears to occur independently from TREM2 signaling. This distinction underscores the possibility that oligodendrocytes may respond directly to amyloid or tau pathology without requiring microglial signaling pathways (Zhou et al.
2020
). Understanding these shared yet distinct molecular pathways could inform the development of broader therapeutic strategies targeting glial cell dysfunction in neurodegenerative diseases. Nevertheless, the observed divergence between species-specific and cell-specific responses highlights the critical need to address the limitations of translating findings from animal models directly to human conditions.
